{{Climate-stub}}

[[File:Roberts torpedo.jpg|thumb|A torpedo designed by Edward A. L. Roberts.]]
A '''torpedo''' is an explosive device used, especially in the early days of the [[petroleum industry]], to fracture the surrounding rock at the bottom of an [[oil well]] to stimulate the flow of oil and to remove built-up [[paraffin wax]] that would restrict the flow. Earlier torpedoes used [[gunpowder]], but the use of [[nitroglycerin]] eventually became widespread. The development of [[hydraulic fracturing]] rendered torpedoes obsolete,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Francis|first=Don|title=Torpedo tales|url=http://www.epmag.com/archives/oilFieldHistory/145.htm|publisher=''E&P Magazine''|date=December 1, 2006|accessdate=June 26, 2010}}</ref> and is the primary fracturing process used today.

== Use ==
A torpedo consisted of canisters that were filled with an explosive and lowered into a well via a rope or wire. [[Gunpowder]] was used in the first torpedoes, but [[nitroglycerin]] was found to work better despite its instability. The well is usually filled with water to prevent the explosion from escaping upwards. Originally, the topmost canister had a [[percussion cap]] that was to detonate the main charge.<ref name="bacon hamor 333">Bacon and Hamor, p. 333</ref> An iron weight was dropped down the well to set the torpedo off. After incidents of premature explosions, a second method was developed in which a tube of the explosive was placed in a larger tube that was packed with sand.<ref name="bacon hamor 333"/> A fuse was wound around the inner tube, connected to a [[blasting cap]]. When the torpedo was to be used, the inner tube was filled with nitroglycerin and corked; the fuse was lit and torpedo was dropped down the well.<ref name="bacon hamor 333"/>

Torpedoes were generally used to remove buildup of paraffin wax from an oil well. Before the use of torpedoes caught on, boiling water or [[benzene]] was often poured down wells to try to dissolve the paraffin.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Michener|first=Carollee|title=Nitroglycerine Saved Many Wells|work=OIL 150|publisher=Oil Region Alliance|location=[[Oil City, Pennsylvania]]|date=April 2007|url=http://www.oil150.com/essays/2007/04/nitroglycerine-saved-many-wells |accessdate=June 21, 2010}}</ref> Torpedoes were also used to fracture the rock to allow the oil to flow more easily.

== History ==
[[Edward A. L. Roberts]] developed the first torpedo and submitted a [[patent application]] in November 1864.<ref name="whiteshot 755">Whiteshot, p. 755</ref> Roberts, an [[American Civil War]] veteran, came up with the concept of using water to "[[wikt:tamp#Verb|tamp]]" the resulting explosion, after watching [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] artillery rounds explode in a canal at the [[Battle of Fredericksburg]].<ref name="whiteshot 755"/><ref name="wells 8">Wells, p. 8</ref> Roberts developed his first torpedoes in 1865 and 1866. In November 1866 he was granted a [[patent]] on his torpedo application, and founded the Roberts Petroleum Torpedo Company.<ref>{{Cite patent|country=US|number=59936|status=patent|title=Improvement of the method of increasing the capacity of oil-wells|gdate=November 20, 1866|inventor=Roberts, Edward A.L.|invent1=Roberts, Edward A. L.}}</ref> William Reed also developed a torpedo design and went on to found a rival company "for the purpose of infringing and breaking down the Roberts patent.<ref name="whiteshot 755"/><ref name="whiteshot 756">Whiteshot, p. 756</ref> Roberts charged $100-200 per torpedo as well as a [[royalties|royalty]] amounting to {{Frac|1|15}} of the increased oil production.<ref name="wells 8"/> To avoid paying the exorbitant fees, an owner of a well would often hire men who illegally produced their own torpedoes and used them at night&mdash;the practice giving rise to term "[[wikt:moonlight#Verb|moonlighting]]". Roberts spent $250,000 to protect his patent from the "moonlighters" by hiring the [[Pinkerton National Detective Agency]] and filing numerous [[lawsuit]]s.<ref name="wells 8"/> Roberts' torpedo patents expired in 1879.<ref name="whiteshot 756"/>
[[File:Otto Torpedo Power Wagon.jpg|thumb|A 1947 [[Dodge]] [[Dodge Power Wagon|Power Wagon]] used to transport torpedoes]]
Torpedoes manufactured today use modern explosives, with the last nitroglycerin torpedo being used on May 5, 1990.<ref>Wells, p. 9</ref>

